  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage Dividend/FCFE Model</h2>
  <p>Valuing banks requires a slightly different approach than non-financial companies. Because debt is "raw material" for a bank and capital expenditures are minimal, traditional Free Cash Flow to Firm (FCFF) doesn't work. Instead, we use <strong>Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE)</strong>, approximated by Net Income, to value the equity directly.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with Net Income as FCFE proxy</h4>
      <p>U.S. Bancorp generated <strong>${(netIncome / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in Net Income to Common in FY2025. This represents the maximum potential cash available to distribute to shareholders after maintaining regulatory capital.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow the cash flow at <strong>4% per year</strong> for 5 years. This is historically in line with a mature super-regional bank navigating normalized net interest margins and modest loan growth.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume growth at <strong>2% forever</strong> — roughly matching inflation. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9.5%</strong> — our required rate of return (Cost of Equity). This accounts for the 10-Year Treasury yield (4.18%) plus a bank-appropriate equity risk premium.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Divide directly by shares</h4>
      <p>Because we use FCFE, the resulting present value is our Equity Value. We do not add net cash or subtract debt. Divide by shares outstanding ({(sharesOutstanding / 1000).toFixed(2)}B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A valuation model is highly sensitive to its inputs. Here's exactly what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        U.S. Bancorp is a stable, mature entity. Post-acquisition integrations are largely complete, and net interest income is normalizing. A 4% growth rate reflects steady economic expansion and modest loan book growth.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (Cost of Equity)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury stands at 4.18%. Given USB's high-quality balance sheet and diversified revenue streams, its beta is typically slightly below 1.0. A 9.5% cost of equity is a reasonable hurdle rate for a high-quality regional bank.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        In perpetuity, banks cannot grow faster than the overall economy without taking on outsized risk. A 2% terminal growth rate assumes USB grows roughly in line with long-term inflation.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

