  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks to the Valuation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Environment:</strong> A persistently inverted yield curve or aggressive rate cuts could squeeze Net Interest Margins (NIM) more than projected.</li>
    <li><strong>Credit Quality:</strong> An economic downturn could force higher provisions for credit losses, notably in Commercial Real Estate (CRE) portfolios, reducing Net Income.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Capital Requirements:</strong> Stricter capital rules (e.g., Basel III Endgame) might restrict the amount of cash that can be distributed as dividends or buybacks, lowering the effective FCFE.</li>
    <li><strong>Deposit Costs:</strong> Fierce competition for deposits could elevate funding costs, putting pressure on profitability.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use Net Income instead of Free Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">For banks, traditional Free Cash Flow is skewed by changes in deposits and loans, which are their operational "inventory." Capital expenditures are small. Instead, Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE) is used, and Net Income is the best starting proxy for the cash generated that theoretically belongs to equity holders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does USB compare to its peers?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">U.S. Bancorp typically trades at a premium to average regional banks due to its high return on tangible common equity (ROTCE) and diversified fee income (payments, trust services), making it less reliant purely on net interest margins.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Are dividends factored into this?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes, inherently. Because we are valuing the total cash theoretically available to equity holders (whether paid out as dividends, buybacks, or retained), the model captures the value of future dividends.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

